<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub6.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showMessage?topicID=4639.topic">Krilen's Suggestions for Caster versus Melee Class Balance</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
In particular, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Krilen</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> claims that existing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician Pets</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are overpowered, and claims that he will demonstrate it by showing that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Greater Vocarate Water</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> will outdamage a 60th <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Paladin</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->: <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub6.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showMessage?topicID=4639.topic&amp;index=20">Mage pets are overpowered and should be nerfed</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> This guy was trying to tell me his pet (not epic, 60 water) had 3.5khp 1kac and higher DPS than me.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Mostly this is BS.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Greater Vocarate</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> pets have no more than 2850 HP, and have low AC.  By giving the pet a complete set of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> summoned armor and focus items, you could add less than 300 AC and maybe a little over 100 hitpoints.  The pet is never higher than 49th level with focus, and has a low ATK compared to players.  It may enjoy some benefits of being an NPC, but has been made more <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;player-like&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> over time.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Where are you going with this conversation?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I want to try to rationally determine whether <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> pets are under powered, over powered, or basically adequate.  While my position is that with the possible exception of raid mobs, pets are basically adequate in power, strong opinions hold otherwise.<br>
<br>
Also, many discussions of class discussion tend to wield DPS like a hammer, and treat every argument like a nail.  Clearly, utility and DPS are two useful considerations.  I find it hopeful that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Paladins</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have found self-acceptance, and would try to accomplish this for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, whom I feel need only a few fixes beyond reducing the risk of pet caused trains and wipeouts.  Part of this may be the temperment of players who chose to play paladins.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  It's almost impossible to try and draw a comparison between hybrid and pure caster. They have NOTHING in common.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->While I agree this is difficult, it is not quite nothing.  Both bring damage and utility to groups and raids.  I am looking for insights into evaluating utility.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Why do you want the mage pet do deal more damage than a paladin?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That is not what I want.<br>
<br>
What I want is to know whether if it were true, would that necessarily mean that pets are unbalanced.<br>
<br>
I also do not have a strong opinion about what fraction of my damage output should be pet and what should my nukes, except that I would not want to have the vast majority of damage concentrated in nukes, as then I would either be encroaching on <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wizard</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> territory, or be little more than a weak <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wizard</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Also, the portion of my damage that is attributable to pets varies with the nature of the encounter.  For magic resistant encounters, then the fact that pets melee allows me to do more damage than if I were purely casting.  Likewise, against high AC mobs, my nukes will be more significant.  If it mostly varied between one third and two thirds, then I have no problem with that.  It's all part of being a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> For soloing, the pet needs to deal slightly less damage than you otherwise you will gain experience slower.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Not necessarily.  A higher damage pet also allows me to kill faster with less downtime, and may mean more experience overall.  For example, at 57-58th level, I was able to solo the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Sarnak Fort</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> outside <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Chardok</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and kill an average of a light blue creature every 45 seconds for hours on end.  For light blues and greens that spawned I conserved mana and basically let the pet solo, and when the spawn was blue, about say a quarter of the spawns, I nuked hard and outdamaged my pet.  I have no problem avoiding aggro.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> For raiding you want the pet damage to be low, otherwise your raid contributions where you are not allowed to use a pet become tiny.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Actually, I want to reduce the risk of pet caused trains and wipeouts, so that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician + Pet</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can be the norm on raids and in groups.  I generally would rather have pet availability than increases in pet strength.  For long fights, I would rather have strong pets so that my raid damage output is not so limited by mana and is effective against raid mobs where melee is appropriate, i.e. most raids.<br>
<br>
I prefer strong pets, and I think I have strong pets.  The question is, are they too strong, and how would we know?<br>
<br>
